While you do this check out the following NVIDIA course "A Beginner's Guide to Autonomous Robots".

Once you are ready with the installation, we will understand the following:-
1. Difference between ROS1 and ROS2 (https://roboticsbackend.com/ros1-vs-ros2-practical-overview/)
2. The general concept of creating packages,nodes, subscribers, publishers, topics,messages and running them. 
Look at the following example which demonstrates subscription,publishing,topic,message concepts with a sample code.

#!/usr/bin/env python3
   
import rospy
from sensor_msgs.msg import Image
from cv_bridge import CvBridge
import cv2
import numpy as np
import time
   
class JetsonVision:
    def __init__(self):
        self.bridge = CvBridge()
        self.image_sub = rospy.Subscriber('/camera/image_raw', Image, self.image_callback)
        self.image_pub = rospy.Publisher('/jetson_vision/processed', Image, queue_size=1)
        self.gpu_mat = cv2.cuda_GpuMat()
           
    def image_callback(self, data):
        try:
            # Convert image to OpenCV format
            cv_image = self.bridge.imgmsg_to_cv2(data, "bgr8")
               
            # Start processing time measurement
            start_time = time.time()
               
            # Upload image to GPU
            self.gpu_mat.upload(cv_image)
               
            # Convert to grayscale on GPU
            gpu_gray = cv2.cuda.cvtColor(self.gpu_mat, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
               
            # Apply Gaussian blur
            gpu_blur = cv2.cuda.GaussianBlur(gpu_gray, (7, 7), 0)
               
            # Detect edges using Canny
            gpu_edges = cv2.cuda.Canny(gpu_blur, 50, 150)
               
            # Download results to CPU memory
            edges = gpu_edges.download()
               
            # Calculate processing time
            process_time = time.time() - start_time
               
            # Add processing time to result image
            cv2.putText(edges, f"Process time: {process_time:.3f}s", (10, 30),
                       cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_SIMPLEX, 0.6, (255, 255, 255), 2)
                          
            # Publish processed image
            self.image_pub.publish(self.bridge.cv2_to_imgmsg(edges, "mono8"))
               
        except Exception as e:
            rospy.logerr(e)
   
if __name__ == '__main__':
    rospy.init_node('jetson_vision', anonymous=True)
    jv = JetsonVision()
    rospy.spin()

3. We will use the following link for running our application
https://github.com/dusty-nv/ros_deep_learning

Follow these steps once you are inside the docker after docker/run.sh --ros=noetic

We want to see how a sample application is run by using camera images.
a. create a catkin workspace and cd into it for creating required packages
mkdir ~/catkin_ws/src ; cd ~/catkin_ws/src
catkin_create_pkg dusty_inference rospy std_msgs sensor_msgs cv_bridge image_transport

b. build the package
cd ~/catkin_ws
catkin_make  #if you get errors at this step, go to the document "catkin_packages_fix" to resolve them
source devel/setup.bash

c. create the camera_node and processor_node inside the dusty_inference/src folder of catkin_ws
The files are given in the ros subfolder. Note that you dont need to always write your own camera_node. Jetson offeres it and publishes 
it for you.You can use it by running the following line 89 or line 94 depending on your camera type. Note the topic name, 
you have to change it inside your processor_node subscription.

sudo apt-get install ros-noetic-usb-cam
rosrun usb_cam usb_cam_node   #this is how you use it later in place of line 125, dont run now
# Publishes to /usb_cam/image_raw

# or 
sudo apt-get install ros-noetic-v4l2-camera
rosrun v4l2_camera v4l2_camera_node     # dont run now, this is how you use it later in place of line 125
#Publishes to /camera/image_raw



d. Inside dusty_inference/CMakeLists.txt, add:
  catkin_install_python(PROGRAMS
  src/camera_node.py
  src/processor_node.py
  DESTINATION ${CATKIN_PACKAGE_BIN_DESTINATION}
)
This means:
Install camera_node.py and processor_node.py into devel/lib/dusty_inference/
ROS will then recognize them as runnable nodes. 

e. Rebuild
cd ~/catkin_ws
catkin_make
source devel/setup.bash

This is during development. During deployment they go in install/lib/dusty_inference/
That happens when you use catkin_make install. But you will not do that now.

f. setup for display in headless mode
sudo apt-get install ros-noetic-image-view


g. Run the nodes
roscore
rosrun dusty_inference camera_node.py            #if you are not using the default line 90,91 or 95,96 
rosrun dusty_inference processor_node.py
rosrun image_view image_view image:=/processed/image

Note standard rosrun has <package_name> <node_name_executable>, the node_name is already an executable after the make.
Also you are explicitly telling what to build in the CMakeLists in (d). The image_view is a standard package with executable name 
image_view, the image parameter is pointing to the topic name (here /processed/image) which is to be used.

You can also use a web view instead of line 120,127 run the following:
sudo apt-get install ros-noetic-web-video-server
rosrun web_video_server web_video_server

On your host browser run the following if you are using web view (line 134) instead of image_view (line 120):-
http://<jetson-ip>:8080/stream?topic=/processed/image

h. Instead of running individual nodes, you can also launch all of them together.
Example: Camera + Processor + Viewer
dusty_inference/launch/system.launch

#xml sample
<launch>
  <!-- Camera node -->
  <node pkg="v4l2_camera" type="v4l2_camera_node" name="camera_node" output="screen"/>

  <!-- Processor node -->
  <node pkg="dusty_inference" type="processor_node.py" name="processor_node" output="screen">
    <!-- Remap so it always listens to /camera/image_raw -->
    <remap from="/usb_cam/image_raw" to="/camera/image_raw"/>
  </node>

  <!-- Web video server for browser viewing -->
  <node pkg="web_video_server" type="web_video_server" name="web_video_server" output="screen"/>
</launch>

roslaunch dusty_inference system.launch #starts all nodes













